      "title": "Introduction to Egla Arufah and the Role of Central Court Representatives",
      "display_title": "Egla Arufah Overview",
      "timestamp": "00:00",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Opening: Transition to Egla Arufah and its connection to Hebrew language requirement",
          "display_title": "Opening & Context",
          "timestamp": "00:00"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Abbahu's explanation: connection between Egla Arufah and Lashon Hakodesh through parallel verses (V'anu V'amru)",
          "display_title": "Abbahu's V'anu V'amru",
          "timestamp": "01:12"
        },
        {
          "title": "Procedure of Egla Arufah: Three representatives from central Beis Din must go out to measure",
          "display_title": "Procedure & Measurement",
          "timestamp": "01:57"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "The Debate over Number of Central Court Representatives (Three vs. Five)",
      "display_title": "Three vs. Five Dispute",
      "timestamp": "03:20",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Tanna Kamma (Rabbi Shimon) says three; Rabbi Yehuda says five based on need for odd-numbered court",
          "display_title": "Initial Positions",
          "timestamp": "03:20"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara analysis: Zkeinecha means two, Shoftecha identified as central judges, not adding to number",
          "display_title": "Zkeinecha Analysis",
          "timestamp": "04:17"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Yehuda's source: Learning from Ziknei Ha'eidah that central court involvement requires five",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Yehuda Source",
          "timestamp": "06:10"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara resolution: The extra vav in V'shoftecha allows Rabbi Yehuda to count it separately for additional members",
          "display_title": "Vav Analysis",
          "timestamp": "08:32"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Rabbi Eliezer ben Yaakov's Expanded View: Involving King and High Priest",
      "display_title": "Rabbi Eliezer Position",
      "timestamp": "10:51",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Eliezer ben Yaakov: Zkeinecha means Sanhedrin, Shoftecha means King and High Priest must participate",
          "display_title": "Eliezer's Interpretation",
          "timestamp": "10:51"
        },
        {
          "title": "Theological significance: National responsibility for unresolved murder—national leaders must take ownership",
          "display_title": "National Responsibility",
          "timestamp": "11:08"
        },
        {
          "title": "Question about whether Rabbi Eliezer requires entire Sanhedrin or just three/five members",
          "display_title": "Entire Sanhedrin Query",
          "timestamp": "13:26"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Analogy to Zaken Mamre: Evidence that Entire Sanhedrin Required for Egla Arufah",
      "display_title": "Zaken Mamre Analogy",
      "timestamp": "17:01",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Case of rebellious elder (Zaken Mamre) meeting Sanhedrin outside official chamber",
          "display_title": "Zaken Mamre Setup",
          "timestamp": "17:01"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara reasoning: Entire Sanhedrin must have left because they cannot leave for mundane purposes without leaving 23 members behind",
          "display_title": "Why They Left",
          "timestamp": "20:09"
        },
        {
          "title": "Baraita lists Egla Arufah measurement as reason for Sanhedrin leaving their chamber, supporting Rabbi Eliezer ben Yaakov's view",
          "display_title": "Baraita Egla Evidence",
          "timestamp": "27:36"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Conditions for Egla Arufah: State of Body and Burial Status",
      "display_title": "Body Conditions",
      "timestamp": "29:57",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Corpse must be Chalal (struck by sword, not strangled) and fully dead, not thrashing on ground",
          "display_title": "Chalal Definition",
          "timestamp": "29:57"
        },
        {
          "title": "Comparison to Shichcha law: whether burial (Tamun) and suspension (Tzaf) exempt from obligation",
          "display_title": "Tamun & Tzaf",
          "timestamp": "30:02"
        },
        {
          "title": "Baraita on sheaves: bottom sheaf is Shichcha (exempt if buried); top sheaf not Shichcha due to possession taken",
          "display_title": "Sheaves Analogy",
          "timestamp": "40:36"
        },
        {
          "title": "Gemara resolution: Debate centers on whether burial under similar object counts as Tamun, not whether Tamun is exempt",
          "display_title": "Tamun Resolution",
          "timestamp": "48:54"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Exposure, Location, and Sanhedrin Authority in Egla Arufah Performance",
      "display_title": "Exposure & Location",
      "timestamp": "29:57",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Corpse must be exposed (Nofel Ba'adamah), not buried under pile or suspended from tree",
          "display_title": "Nofel Ba'adamah",
          "timestamp": "29:57"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Two Corpses Stacked and Exposure Requirements for Egla Arufah",
      "display_title": "Stacked Corpses",
      "timestamp": "45:57",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Question: two corpses one on top of the other—which (if either) qualifies for Egla Arufah ritual?",
          "display_title": "Problem Statement",
          "timestamp": "45:57"
        },
        {
          "title": "Multiple possible interpretations of whether similar-to-similar burial/suspension has different status than other burial",
          "display_title": "Min B'Mino Issue",
          "timestamp": "46:26"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Exposure, Location, and Sanhedrin Authority in Egla Arufah Performance (continued)",
      "display_title": "Exposure & Location (II)",
      "timestamp": "52:04",
      "micro_segments": [
        {
          "title": "Corpse must be in field (Ba'Sadeh), not floating on water",
          "display_title": "Ba'Sadeh Requirement",
          "timestamp": "52:04"
        },
        {
          "title": "Rabbi Elazar disagrees: only Chalal (sword-struck) matters; rejects other technical exemptions",
          "display_title": "Rabbi Elazar Position",
          "timestamp": "52:13"
        },
        {
          "title": "Corpse near border town or majority non-Jewish city exempt because murder is too common (not a rare finding)",
          "display_title": "Border Town Exemption",
          "timestamp": "53:32"
        },
        {
          "title": "Corpse near city without Beis Din: measure to closest city WITH Beis Din (Ziknei Ha'ir required)",
          "display_title": "Beis Din Requirement",
